The old Chartulary of Scone is a small thin folio written on parch- ment, consisting of 32 leaves, and containing transcripts of 83 different deeds. It is defective in several place8‚ and the sheets which remain have not been properly bound. This chartulary does not contain the foundation charter of the Abbey by Alexander Ι. The earliest deed is a bull of Pope Alexander II. in 1164; and with the exception of the four deeds which occur at the end of the volume, the latest are the charters by Robert I., which are dated in the aoth year of his reign, or 1326. From that circumstance, and from the character of the writing, we may pronounce it to have been written not later than the year 1350. This volume formed part of Sir J ames Balfour’s collection, and was purchased in 1698, along with his other MSS„ by the Faculty of Advocates, in whose library it now is.

The other and more recent chartulary is a larger folio on parch- ment, bound in blue morocco.
